{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3425bf9-8fe8-4b44-81ff-9c24b13ce702","content":"TUnit runs on Microsoft.Testing.Platform and uses `--treenode-filter` with a path-like syntax (`/assembly/namespace/class/test`):\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args. The wildcards match any assembly and namespace, filtering to just the `SmsNotificationTests` class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6c098d77-4fa4-480a-b286-c12e42d3d5a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nTUnit uses its own `--treenode-filter` for filtering. To filter by class name, the syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit is built on Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The way to run TUnit tests:\n\n1. Since TUnit projects have `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, they are executable. You can run them with `dotnet run` or build and execute directly.\n\n\n2. With `dotnet test`, TUnit uses MTP. For MTP, the tree-node filter uses a path-like syntax with `/assembly/namespace/class/test` hierarchy. I can filter by the `SmsNotificationTests` class using glob-like patterns with either `dotnet run` or `dotnet test` followed by the `--treenode-filter` flag with the pattern `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*`.","outputTokens":478,"requestId":"4809:286947:5B78053:6339AFF:69FBEA40"},"id":"1c6fed26-1d33-4ea2-895d-156dd1863ee4","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:26:37.635Z","parentId":"10c4c812-723f-4f71-aa2e-4f32c4507b68"}
